Fig. 1. (a) Oscillating water density in model pores of increasing pore radius R. The water density n(t) (in units of the bulk water density nbulk) over the simulation time shows strong ﬂuctuations on a greater than ns time scale (50-ps moving average smoothing). Two distinctive states are visible: open at approximately nbulk (liquid water) and closed with very little or no water in the pore (water vapor). (b) The pore model consists of methane pseudo atoms of van der Waals radius 0.195 nm. A water molecule is drawn to scale. (c) Permeant water molecules in a R ϭ 0.55-nm pore as it switches from the open to the closed state. Z-coordinates of the water oxygen atoms are drawn every 2 ps. The mouth and pore region are indicated by horizontal broken and solid lines. Five trajectories are shown explicitly. The white water molecule permeates the pore within 54 ps, whereas the black one requires only Ϸ10 ps.

The integration time step was 2 fs and coordinates were saved every 2 ps. With periodic boundary conditions, long-range electrostatic interactions were computed with a particle mesh Ewald method [real space cutoff 1 nm, grid spacing 0.15 nm, fourth-order interpolation (29)], whereas the short-range van der Waals forces were calculated within a radius of 1 nm. The neighbor list (radius 1 nm) was updated every 10 steps.
Weak coupling algorithms (30) were used to simulate at constant temperature (T ϭ 300 K, time constant 0.1 ps) and pressure (P ϭ 1 bar, compressibility 4.5 ϫ 10Ϫ5 barϪ1, time constant 1 ps) with the x and y dimensions of the simulation cell held fixed at 6 nm (or 3.9 nm for the 80-ns simulation of the R ϭ 0.35-nm pore). The length in z was 4.6 nm in both cases (ensuring bulk-like water behavior far from the membrane mimetic).
The large (small) system contained Ϸ700 (300) methane pseudo atoms and 4,000 (1,500) SPC water molecules. Simulation times Tsim ranged from 52 to 80 ns (altogether 460 ns). Bulk properties of SPC water were obtained from simulations in a cubic cell of length 3 nm (895 molecules) with isotropic pressure coupling at 300 K and 1 bar for 5 ns. Analysis. Time courses and density. For the density time courses (Fig. 1a) the pore occupancy N(t), i.e., the number of water molecules within the pore cavity (a cylinder of height LP ϭ 0.8 nm containing the pore-lining atoms) was counted. The density n(t) is given by N(t) divided by the water-accessible pore volume V ϭ LP ␲Re2ff and normalized to the bulk density of SPC water at 300 K and 1 bar (nbulk ϭ 53.67 Ϯ 0.03 mol⅐literϪ1). The effective pore radius for all pores is Reff ϭ R Ϫ ␦R. Choosing ␦R ϭ 0.03 nm fixes the density ͗N͘͞V in the (most bulk-like) R ϭ 1.0-nm pore at the value calculated from the radial density, R0Ϫ1͐0R0 n(r)dr, where R0 ϭ 1.05 nm is the radius at which n(r) vanishes.
The density n(r) was determined on a grid of cubic cells with spacing 0.05 nm. Two- and one-dimensional densities were computed by integrating out the appropriate coordinate(s). A probabilistic interpretation of n(r) leads to the definition of the potential of mean force (PMF) of a water molecule ␤F(r) ϭ Ϫln[n(r)͞nbulk] with ␤Ϫ1 ϭ kBT, via Boltzmann sampling of states. Free-energy density and chemical potential. The Helmholtz free energy as a function of the pore occupancy N at constant T ϭ 300 K for a given pore with volume V was calculated from the probability distribution p(N) of the occupancy as ␤F(T, V, N) ϭ Ϫln p(N) and transformed into a free-energy density f(T, n) ϭ F͞V. A fourth-order polynomial in n was least-square-fitted to ␤f(T, n). The chemical potential ␮(T, n) ϭ Ѩf(T, n)͞Ѩn was calculated as the analytical derivative of the polynomial.

