which describes how vapor at pressure p relative to its bulksaturated pressure p0 coexists in equilibrium with its liquid. Liquid and vapor are divided by an interfacial meniscus of curvature 1͞r (r Ͼ 0 if the surface is convex); ␥lv is the surface tension between liquid and vapor and vl the molecular volume of the liquid. Although the Kelvin equation is not expected to be quantitative in systems of dimensions of only a few molecular diameters it is still useful for obtaining a qualitative picture. Curvature 1͞r and contact angle ␪ in a cylindrical pore of radius R are related by R ϭ r cos ␪. With Young’s equation, ␥wv ϭ ␥wl ϩ ␥lv cos ␪, Eq. 1 becomes

